\textbf{
Electron spins in gate-defined quantum dots provide a promising platform for quantum computation \cite{Loss1998,Veldhorst2015,Nowack2011,Koppens2006,Bluhm2011,Petta2005,Nowack2007,Maune2012}.
In particular, spin-based quantum computing in gallium arsenide takes advantage of the high quality of semiconducting materials, reliability in fabricating arrays of quantum dots, and accurate qubit operations \cite{Martins2015,Nowack2007,Petta2005,Maune2012,Foletti2009,Dial2013}.
However, the effective magnetic noise arising from the hyperfine interaction with uncontrolled nuclear spins in the host lattice constitutes a major source of decoherence \cite{Petta2005,Koppens2006,Bluhm2011,Martins2015}. 
Low frequency nuclear noise, responsible for fast (10 ns) inhomogeneous dephasing \cite{Petta2005}, can be removed by echo techniques \cite{Viola1998, Barthel2010, Medford2012}. High frequency nuclear noise, recently studied via echo revivals \cite{Bluhm2011}, occurs in narrow frequency bands related to differences in Larmor precession of the three isotopes $\mathbf{^{69}Ga}$, $\mathbf{^{71}Ga}$,  and $\mathbf{^{75}As}$ \cite{Cywinski2009,Cywinski2009a, Neder2011}.
Here we show that both low and high frequency nuclear noise can be filtered by appropriate dynamical decoupling sequences, resulting in a substantial enhancement of spin qubit coherence times. Using nuclear notch filtering, we demonstrate a spin coherence time ($\mathbf{T_{2}}$) of 0.87 ms, five orders of magnitude longer than inhomogeneous dephasing.
}


