Our qubit is implemented in a gate-defined double dot, with a potential that can be manipulated via nanosecond voltage pulses applied to gate electrodes ${V_\mathrm{L}}$, ${V_\mathrm{M}}$ and ${V_\mathrm{R}}$ (Fig.~\ref{fig1}a and Methods). 
The qubit states are encoded in the two-electron spin singlet state, $\ket{S} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{{\uparrow\downarrow}} - \ket{{\downarrow\uparrow}})$, and the spin triplet state,  $\ket{T_0} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{{\uparrow\downarrow}} + \ket{{\downarrow\uparrow}})$, where the arrows indicate the spin projections of the electrons in the left and right dots. 
These qubit states are energetically separated from the spin-polarized two-electron states, $\ket{\uparrow\uparrow}$ and $\ket{\downarrow\downarrow}$, by an external magnetic field ${\bf {B}}^{\rm ext}$ \cite{Petta2005,Taylor2007}. 

As illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig1}b, the local Zeeman energy in dot $d = {\rm L,R}$ is perturbed by the Overhauser field ${\bf {B}}^{{\rm nuc}}_d$ arising from the hyperfine interaction with the nuclear spin bath. 
In our device, each electron is in contact with $\sim 10^6$ nuclear spins, comprised of three species:
 $^{69}$Ga, $^{71}$Ga and $^{75}$As \cite{Petta2005,Taylor2007,Bluhm2011,Neder2011,Koppens2006}. 

The Bloch sphere of the $S$-$T_0$ qubit is shown in Fig.~\ref{fig1}c.  Bold arrows indicate the rotation axes associated with the exchange interaction, $J$, and the gradient of the effective field between the dots, $\Delta {B^\mathrm{tot}} = {B^\mathrm{tot}}_{\rm L} - {B^\mathrm{tot}}_{\rm R}$, where ${B^\mathrm{tot}}_d = \sqrt{|{\bf {B}}^{\rm ext} + {\bf {B}}^{{\rm nuc}}_d|^2}$ is the magnitude of the total effective field in dot ${d}$~\cite{Foletti2009}.
Single-shot readout of the qubit is accomplished using spin-to-charge conversion followed by readout of a proximal sensor dot \cite{Barthel2009, Barthel2010} (see Methods).
Note that transverse nuclear field gradients tilt the quantization axes in the two dots relative to each other.
For large external fields this primarily leads to a minor redefinition of the qubit subspace~\cite{Neder2011}; for simplicity throughout this work we refer to the states in the qubit subspace by the conventional labels $S$ and $T_0$.

Overhauser field fluctuations in each dot are non-Markovian, with low frequency (power-law) spectral content parallel to the external field, denoted ${B_\mathrm{z}^\mathrm{nuc}}$ (suppressing the dot index), and narrow-band spectral components at the nuclear Larmor frequency scale perpendicular to the external field, denoted ${\bf {B}}^{\rm nuc}_\perp$. Low frequency fluctuations arise primarily from nuclear spin diffusion~\cite{Reilly2008}, driven by dipole-dipole interactions between neighboring nuclei, and electron mediated flip-flops \cite{DeSousa2003,Yao2006,Cywinski2009,Cywinski2009a}.
High frequency fluctuations of ${\bf {B}}^{\rm nuc}_\perp$ arise primarily due to the megahertz-scale relative Larmor precession of different nuclear spins~\cite{Bluhm2011,Neder2011}. 
The transverse Overhauser field ${\bf {B}}^{\rm nuc}_\perp$ is given by the sum of contributions ${\bf {B}}_\perp^{^{69}\mathrm{Ga}}$, ${\bf {B}}_\perp^{^{71}\mathrm{Ga}}$, and ${\bf {B}}_\perp^{^{75}\mathrm{As}}$ of the three isotopic species, each of which precesses at its own  Larmor frequency, see Fig.~\ref{fig1}e.
This leads to modulations of the total field in each dot, ${B^\mathrm{tot}}$, which are concentrated near the {\it differences} of the nuclear Larmor frequencies, and contribute quadratically to the qubit splitting.


