To decouple the qubit from the multiscale nuclear noise, we employ the Carr-Purcell-Meiboom-Gill (CPMG) pulse sequence shown in Fig.~2a. 
We first initialize the double dot in a spin singlet by temporarily loading two electrons into the left dot.
Then we quickly separate the electrons in the double-well potential, thereby rapidly turning off the exchange interaction, $J$. In this configuration, the gradient of the total effective field, $\Delta {B^\mathrm{tot}}$, causes uncontrolled qubit rotation around the horizontal axis of the Bloch sphere in Fig.~\ref{fig1}c. 
After a time $\tau/2$, an exchange pulse is applied by temporarily lowering the barrier between dots with a voltage pulse on gate ${V_\mathrm{M}}$ \cite{Martins2015,Reed2015,Bertrand2015}, implementing a $\pi$ rotation around the vertical axis of the Bloch sphere. 
We repeat this set of operations $n$ times (where $n$ is even) and, after a total evolution time $T = n\tau$, read out the state of the qubit. The fraction of singlet outcomes is denoted $P_S$. Setting $n=1$ implements a Hahn-echo sequence, and allows comparison to previous work \cite{Bluhm2011,Childress2006}.

For quasistatic nuclear noise, the effective field acting on the qubit before and after the $\pi$ pulse is nearly the same, causing the qubit state to be refocussed to the singlet after an interval $\tau/2$.
For nonstatic nuclear noise with power spectrum $S(f)$, Hahn and CPMG sequences do not eliminate noise, but rather act as a filter of the noise in the frequency domain~\cite{Martinis2003,Cywinski2008,Biercuk2010,Kabytayev2014}.
